rescuers when trapped under debris?',24),(303,'C','EASY','Only 6 hours maximum','24 hours under any circumstances','72 hours ΓÇö longer with water available','Exactly 1 week always','What is the average survival window under collapse rubble?',24),(304,'D','EASY','It is illegal to enter under any law','Rescue teams will not come if bystanders enter first','The air inside is immediately toxic after collapse','Secondary collapses kill more rescue volunteers than the original event','Why should bystanders NOT enter a partially collapsed building?',24),(305,'C','EASY','One continuous loud shout without stopping','Five rapid taps followed by silence','Three taps or three shouts repeated at regular intervals','Any repeated noise pattern you can manage','What is the international distress signal for a trapped person?',24),(306,'D','EASY','Your bare hand pressed firmly over the mouth','Nothing ΓÇö breathing normally is always best','A wet cloth only if fire is also present','A cloth to filter dangerous dust particles','What should you cover your mouth with when trapped under collapse debris?',24),(307,'C','EASY','911','999','112','100','What phone number works without a SIM card to call emergency services in India?',24),(308,'D','MEDIUM','Finding an existing gap large enough to escape through','Creating noise to help signal nearby rescuers','Removing large debris pieces to completely free yourself','Pushing debris away to create a small protective space improving survival odds','What is void space creation when trapped in rubble?',24),(309,'D','MEDIUM','It may collapse the entire debris pile immediately','Rescuers cannot hear tapping over movement noise','It raises body temperature to dangerous levels','It stirs up dust reducing air quality and consumes oxygen faster','Why is unnecessary movement dangerous when trapped under debris?',24),(310,'D','MEDIUM','Steel frame buildings with glass curtain walls','Reinforced concrete buildings of any height','Large timber frame buildings','Non-engineered unreinforced masonry buildings','What construction type is most likely to collapse in an earthquake?',24),(311,'D','MEDIUM','A collapse in a neighbouring building caused by vibration','A collapse caused by heavy rescue equipment being used','The collapse of upper floors only after lower floors stabilise','Further collapse of a partially damaged building after the initial collapse event','What is a secondary collapse?',24),(312,'D','MEDIUM','Heavy rainfall accumulating on the roof over time','Vibration from nearby road traffic only','Humidity building up inside the walls over years','Soil liquefaction, erosion, and overloading the structure beyond design limits','What causes foundation failure in buildings?',24),(313,'D','MEDIUM','Physically digging through debris to reach survivors','Carrying medical supplies directly to trapped survivors','Alerting bystanders to the risk of secondary collapse','Locating survivors by scent in areas where acoustic devices cannot reach','What is the role of search dogs in urban search and rescue operations?',24),(314,'D','MEDIUM','Use the torch function constantly for comfort and visibility','Call every person in their contacts list','Leave it switched on permanently so rescuers can track it','Conserve it and call 112 at regular intervals rather than continuously','What should a trapped person do with a mobile phone battery?',24),(315,'D','MEDIUM','Water is needed to fight small dust fires in the debris','Staying hydrated primarily helps prevent panic attacks','Water signals rescuers through acoustic detection devices','Dehydration becomes life-threatening within 24 to 72 hours and water extends the survival window','Why is water conservation critical when trapped under debris?',24),(316,'D','HARD','To communicate orders between rescue workers on site','To detect dangerous gas leaks throughout the rubble','To measure the structural stability of remaining sections','To detect sounds of tapping, breathing, or heartbeats through rubble to locate survivors','What is the purpose of acoustic listening devices in urban search and rescue?',24),(317,'D','HARD','When only the roof collapses onto the top floor','When walls fall outward leaving all the floors intact','When the entire building tilts and falls sideways','When floor slabs fall and stack on top of each other crushing all interior spaces','What is pancake collapse in building failure?',24),(318,'D','HARD','Gas leaks cause additional structural weakening of the debris','Gas leaks only affect people in areas above the collapse zone','Gas dissipates too quickly outdoors to be any real risk','Fractured gas lines combined with debris dust and structural sparks create explosion risk','Why are gas leaks especially dangerous after a building collapse?',24),(319,'D','HARD','Very thick solid exterior walls throughout the structure','A large number of windows for escape routes','A very deep basement below the structure','Ductile reinforced concrete frames that flex without sudden brittle failure','What building design feature most improves earthquake survivability for occupants?',24),(320,'D','HARD','Drop all belongings and run immediately for the exit','Drop to the floor and roll toward the nearest exterior wall','Hold onto any fixed structure while remaining fully upright','Drop to the ground under a sturdy surface and hold on until shaking stops','What is the DROP and HOLD technique when collapse begins inside a building?',24),(321,'D','HARD','Cameras photograph the collapse scene from safe outside positions','Cameras are permanently attached to all rescue dogs','Cameras detect heat signatures of survivors through thick debris','Flexible cameras are threaded through small gaps in debris to visually search for survivors','How do rescue cameras assist urban search and rescue operations?',24),(322,'D','HARD','Fast, Slow, and Standard response time classifications','Local, Regional, and National geographic classifications','Medical, Technical, and Logistics capability classifications','Light, Medium, and Heavy ΓÇö classified by capability to search and rescue in collapse structures','What is the INSARAG classification system for urban search and rescue teams?',24),(323,'D','HARD','Old buildings always use superior quality materials','Age makes buildings stronger through natural settlement over time','Modern buildings collapse more easily because they are much taller','They were designed without seismic load calculations and use brittle construction materials','Why do buildings built before modern seismic codes pose higher collapse risk?',24),(324,'D','HARD','The weight of all floors pressing vertically downward','The force of groundwater against foundation walls','The thermal expansion force of building materials in heat','Horizontal force from wind or earthquakes that buildings must be specifically designed to resist','What is lateral load in building structural engineering?',24),(325,'D','HARD','Painting over all visible cracks to seal and monitor them','Removing all furniture to significantly reduce the building weight','Adding extra floors to increase the counterbalancing weight','Shoring ΓÇö temporary supports installed by engineers to stabilise damaged load-bearing elements','What immediate structural action reduces collapse risk in a damaged building after an earthquake?',24),(326,'A','EASY','Compressive asphyxia ΓÇö chest pressure preventing breathing','Being directly trampled underfoot','Heart attack from extreme fear','Dehydration from the crowd heat','What is the primary cause of death in a stampede?',25),(327,'B','EASY','Only when physically touching others on all sides','Four to five people per square metre','Ten or more people per square metre','Only in outdoor spaces without barriers','What crowd density makes independent movement impossible and dangerous?',25),(328,'D','EASY','Arms raised above the head to signal danger to security','Arms pushing strongly outward to create personal space','Arms held tightly at the sides to reduce your physical width','Arms held up in front of the chest to protect the airway and create breathing space','What is the boxer stance technique in crowd safety?',25),(329,'D','EASY','Lie completely flat on your back and stretch both arms out wide','Stand up immediately at any cost no matter what','Curl face down with both arms tightly covering the head','Curl on your side with knees to chest, cover head, face direction of crowd movement','What is the survival position if you fall in a stampede?',25),(330,'D','EASY','The food and water station locations for later','The security personnel and their positions','The centre of the crowd for the best visibility','The nearest two exits ΓÇö not just the main entrance','What should you identify first upon entering any crowded venue?',25),(331,'D','EASY','A planned coordinated movement directed by event security','The normal forward movement of a crowd toward the stage','A backward push intentionally created by security personnel','A sudden wave of uncontrolled movement through the crowd that can knock people off their feet','What is a crowd surge?',25),(332,'D','EASY','Your belongings will immediately be stolen by others','It slows down the overall crowd flow significantly','Only applies when the crowd is actively moving forward','You may not be able to stand up again due to crowd pressure from above','Why should you never bend down to pick up a dropped item in a dense crowd?',25),(333,'D','MEDIUM','It is physically faster than moving directly against the crowd','It signals security personnel that you urgently need help','It confuses the crowd movement and creates extra space','It reduces the force against you while reaching the less dense safer edge','What does moving diagonally toward the edge of a crowd achieve?',25),(334,'D','MEDIUM','It is physically impossible in any crowd of any size','It only fails in very small crowds of under 50 people','Security will physically remove you for causing disruption','It exhausts you quickly and creates turbulence making conditions worse for everyone','Why is fighting directly against crowd flow dangerous?',25),(335,'D','MEDIUM','The crowd is enthusiastically enjoying the event in a wave','Security personnel are moving through the crowd on patrol','A performer or celebrity is moving through the crowd area','A crowd surge is occurring and conditions may become dangerous ΓÇö move toward the edge now','What does a ripple effect seen moving through a distant crowd indicate?',25),(336,'D','MEDIUM','Only when you see security personnel physically running','Only when you see someone fall near your position','Only when the official event has fully ended','Early when you first sense the crowd becoming dangerously dense before pressure fully builds','When should you leave a crowded venue to avoid a potential stampede?',25),(337,'D','MEDIUM','Only the combined force of the people directly surrounding you','500 newtons maximum in any real crowd situation','The equivalent force of just a single large person','Over 4500 newtons ΓÇö enough to bend solid steel barriers','What force can crowd pressure in a dense crush generate?',25),(338,'D','MEDIUM','Ensuring enough tickets are sold to cover all event costs','Installing comprehensive surveillance camera systems only','Providing enough food and water to keep people stationary','Multiple clearly marked exits, crowd monitors, flow barriers, and emergency communication systems','What is the primary responsibility of event organisers in stampede prevention?',25),(339,'D','MEDIUM','Your full name and contact number clearly','Specific instructions to stop the entire crowd','Nothing at all ΓÇö conserve all your energy completely','Scream loudly for help to attract bystanders on the edge who may pull you out','What should you shout if you fall in a stampede?',25),(340,'D','MEDIUM','The intense noise generated by a very large crowd','The significant heat generated by a densely packed crowd','The vibration of the ground surface under a large crowd','Unpredictable random movements where people are pushed in multiple directions simultaneously','What is crowd turbulence in the physics of stampede events?',25),(341,'D','MEDIUM','A surprise performer has arrived unexpectedly at the venue','The sound system is malfunctioning and causing confusion','Security is making an important public announcement nearby','A crush or collapse is likely occurring in that direction ΓÇö move away immediately','What does screaming from a direction you cannot see the cause of indicate in a crowd?',25),(342,'D','HARD','Roll away from the crowd completely before attempting to stand','Grab the nearest person legs to pull yourself upright','Wait patiently until the entire crowd has passed you','Time a rise during a momentary gap ΓÇö push up on all fours first then stand quickly','How do you correctly get up from the ground in a stampede?',25),(343,'D','HARD','Bidirectional flow using the same shared pathways for all movement','Radial flow moving from the centre outward in all directions','Random flow with multiple freely crossing paths throughout','Unidirectional flow ΓÇö designing completely separate entry and exit paths so crowds never meet head-on','What is the crowd flow model event planners use to prevent deadly crushes?',25),(344,'D','HARD','People at the front panic for no apparent reason','The front barriers always collapse under any sustained crowd pressure','Performers attract people forward creating a dangerous vacuum effect','People at the front are compressed against barriers while pressure from behind continuously builds from new arrivals','Why do crowd crushes happen near the front of a concert even when the back area is uncrowded?',25),(345,'D','HARD','A temporary flexible barrier ΓÇö it absorbs crowd impact force','The centre of a completely open floor space area','Near an emergency door which always opens safely outward','A solid permanent wall ΓÇö it does not give way under any crowd pressure','What is the safest structural element to stand near in any crowded venue?',25),(346,'D','HARD','The barriers used were far too weak for the crowd size','The overall crowd was simply far too large in total numbers','The music was too loud causing widespread disorientation and panic','A single tunnel became both entry and exit creating opposing crowd flows that caused fatal compression','What proved fatally flawed in the Love Parade 2010 stampede in Germany?',25),(347,'D','HARD','The two causes of death are completely identical in mechanism','Trampling is always the primary cause of death in stampedes','Compressive asphyxia only occurs when a person is already lying on the ground','Surrounding crowd pressure prevents chest expansion for breathing even while the person remains upright','How does compressive asphyxia kill compared to trampling?',25),(348,'D','HARD','10 persons per square metre is the recognised international standard','1 person per square metre is always required for all events','No internationally recognised standard currently exists','A maximum of 2 persons per square metre for standing events in most safety standards','What is the venue capacity safety standard that prevents dangerous crowd density?',25),(349,'D','HARD','People are physically faster and stronger when panicking in darkness','Security emergency response is always much slower in complete darkness','Emergency exit signs are completely hidden and invisible in total darkness','Darkness prevents people from seeing crowd conditions ahead causing critically delayed reaction to danger','What human behaviour pattern makes crowd stampede casualties significantly higher in complete darkness?',25),(350,'D','HARD','Collective intelligence naturally guiding the entire group toward safety','A subconscious leader directing all movement without anyone realising','Pure random statistical chance affecting everyone simultaneously','Social contagion ΓÇö one person startled reaction spreads instantly through the crowd creating mass panic','What psychological phenomenon causes a crowd to suddenly move in the same direction without any clear cause?',25),(351,'D','EASY','Any wind above 60 km/h','Wind gusts above 200 km/h only','Sustained winds above 50 km/h','Sustained winds exceeding 119 km/h','What wind speed defines a cyclone?',26),(352,'A','EASY','Storm surge ΓÇö ocean water pushed onshore','Lightning strikes during the storm','Flying debris from destroyed buildings','Tornadoes spawned by the cyclone','What kills more people in a cyclone than the wind itself?',26),(353,'C','EASY','At least 12 hours','At least 24 hours','At least 72 hours','Supplies not needed if sheltering at home','How many hours of supplies should a cyclone emergency kit contain?',26),(354,'D','EASY','The cyclone has completely passed your area','The cyclone has weakened significantly and safely','Wind will not return for several more hours','The back eyewall is about to hit with equal or greater force','What does the sudden calm during the eye of a cyclone mean?',26),(355,'D','EASY','Near a window to monitor outside conditions','On the top floor for the best structural stability','Near exterior walls for the quickest exit route','An interior room on the lowest floor away from all windows','Where should you shelter inside a building during a cyclone?',26),(356,'C','EASY','Yes if the tree is large and has strong roots','Yes if it is the only available shelter option','Never ΓÇö trees are the first casualties of high winds','Only if the tree is a concrete reinforced structure','Should you shelter under a tree during a cyclone?',26),(357,'D','MEDIUM','Open them slightly to equalise internal pressure','Tape them with masking tape to prevent shattering','Cover them only with heavy curtains inside','Board them up with plywood or install storm shutters','What should you do with windows before a cyclone arrives?',26),(358,'D','MEDIUM','Only small drinking bottles for personal use','Swimming pools to use as an emergency water reserve','No need to store water if you have tap access','Bathtubs and large containers as water supply will be disrupted','What should you fill before a cyclone makes landfall?',26),(359,'D','MEDIUM','Run toward any visible building immediately','Take cover under a highway overpass bridge','Stand firmly against any solid wall you can find','Lie flat in a ditch covering your head to stay low','What should you do if caught completely outdoors during a cyclone with no shelter?',26),(360,'D','MEDIUM','Bridges attract lightning repeatedly during storms','Bridges flood first from storm surge water','Bridges vibrate and collapse easily in high wind','Extreme winds are stronger on elevated exposed structures and can throw people off','Why are bridges particularly dangerous during a cyclone?',26),(361,'C','MEDIUM','NDRF ΓÇö National Disaster Response Force','ISRO ΓÇö Indian Space Research Organisation','IMD ΓÇö India Meteorological Department','INCOIS ΓÇö Indian National Centre for Ocean Information Services','Which Indian agency issues official cyclone warnings?',26),(362,'D','MEDIUM','Leave immediately with your emergency go-bag','Follow official designated evacuation routes','Inform authorities if you truly cannot evacuate','Stay behind to protect your property from damage','What should you NOT do when a mandatory evacuation order is issued?',26),(363,'D','MEDIUM','Wind can only move very lightweight vehicles','Insurance does not cover cyclone vehicle damage','Vehicles block emergency response evacuation routes','Storm surge and flooding can rapidly submerge and destroy vehicles','Why should vehicles be moved from low-lying areas before a cyclone?',26),(364,'D','HARD','The western coastline facing the Arabian Sea only','Both coastlines are equally vulnerable at all times','Neither coastline ΓÇö cyclones only affect island territories','The eastern coastline facing the Bay of Bengal','Which Indian coastline is most vulnerable to cyclones?',26),(365,'D','HARD','Open windows increase interior sound levels only','Open windows work only for weaker Category 1 cyclones','This is actually a myth ΓÇö open windows do equalise pressure safely','Open windows allow wind inside creating uplift pressure that can blow off the roof','Why does opening windows during a cyclone NOT equalise pressure safely?',26),(366,'D','HARD','The eastern coast simply has more population density','Prevailing western winds push all storms toward the east coast','No natural geographic barriers exist along the entire coast','Shallow warm water and a funnel shape that intensifies storms significantly','What makes the Bay of Bengal particularly dangerous for cyclone formation?',26),(367,'D','HARD','Both terms mean exactly the same thing in practice','Watch means a cyclone has been sighted, Warning means conditions are right','Only warnings require any immediate protective action','Watch means cyclone conditions possible within 48 hours, Warning means within 24 hours','What is the difference between a cyclone watch and cyclone warning issued by IMD?',26),(368,'D','HARD','Storm surge and rain flooding are completely identical phenomena','Storm surge is only caused by very heavy rainfall during the storm','Storm surge only occurs in very severe cyclones above Category 4','Storm surge is ocean water pushed by wind onto land ΓÇö different from rain flooding which comes from above','What is cyclone storm surge and how does it differ from rain flooding?',26),(369,'D','HARD','The eye wall shrinking very rapidly in size','The storm surge doubling in height within hours','The cyclone changing direction rapidly and unexpectedly','A wind speed increase of at least 55 km/h within 24 hours making accurate forecasting very difficult','What is rapid intensification in a cyclone?',26),(370,'D','HARD','It hits cold air over land that freezes the storm structure','Land friction immediately and completely destroys the rotation','It splits into multiple smaller weaker storms over land','It loses its energy source of warm ocean water when it moves over land','Why does a cyclone weaken rapidly after making landfall?',26),(371,'D','HARD','Leave them at home as they are replaceable items','Mail them to a safe remote location beforehand','Photograph them only and store copies digitally','Store them in waterproof bags and take them when evacuating','What should you do with important documents before a cyclone strikes?',26),(372,'D','HARD','The outer edge boundary of the entire storm system','The calm centre of the cyclone where winds drop','The storm surge front that moves ahead of the cyclone','The ring of intense thunderstorms surrounding the calm eye containing the strongest winds','What is the eyewall in a cyclone?',26),(373,'D','HARD','Drowning risk from the remaining flood water only','Water contamination affecting only crops and agriculture','The standing water itself is not a health risk after the storm','Mosquito breeding causing disease outbreaks such as dengue and malaria','After a cyclone what is the primary ongoing health risk from standing water?',26),(374,'D','HARD','Kerala ΓÇö facing the Arabian Sea directly','Karnataka ΓÇö central position on the coastline','Goa ΓÇö located at the midpoint of the western coast','Odisha and Andhra Pradesh ΓÇö historically the most frequently struck states','What is the most cyclone-affected state on India eastern coastline by historical frequency?',26),(375,'D','HARD','63 km/h sustained winds','89 km/h sustained winds','102 km/h sustained winds','118 km/h sustained winds','What is the minimum wind speed for a Very Severe Cyclonic Storm classification by IMD?',26);
