INSERT INTO `virtual_drills` VALUES (1,'B','Open the door to see what is happening','Alert your teacher and classmates without opening the door','Quietly leave alone through the window','Wait to see if the smell gets stronger before doing anything','You smell smoke coming from under your classroom door. You cannot see any fire. What is your FIRST action?',7,1),(2,'C','Quickly grab your bag and phone then follow','Tell the teacher to wait for you','Leave everything and evacuate immediately','Ask a friend to grab your things while you leave','Your teacher shouts to evacuate immediately. Your phone and bag are still at your desk. What do you do?',7,1),(3,'B','Run fast through the smoke while holding your breath','Get low and crawl under the smoke toward the staircase','Turn back and try the lift instead','Stand still and shout for help until someone comes','You are evacuating and see thick smoke ahead in the corridor. The staircase is at the end of that corridor. What do you do?',7,1),(4,'C','Open it quickly and run down before the heat builds further','Kick it open from a distance to avoid your hand burning','Do not open it ΓÇö find an alternative exit route','Wait near the door for it to cool down naturally','You reach a staircase door. You touch it with the back of your hand and it is very hot. What do you do?',7,1),(5,'B','Jump immediately ΓÇö the fire is more dangerous than the fall','Stay near the window, signal and shout to rescuers, and wait ΓÇö do not jump','Break the glass and try to climb down using curtains tied together','Go back into the smoke to look for another exit you might have missed','You are on the 3rd floor. All exits are blocked. You are at a window and can see the ground below. What is your best action?',7,1),(6,'C','Run back inside immediately to find them','Shout their name from outside and hope they hear you','Tell a teacher or firefighter immediately ΓÇö do NOT go back inside yourself','Wait 10 minutes at the assembly point before reporting it','You have evacuated safely. You realise your close friend is not at the assembly point. What do you do?',7,1),(7,'B','Which colour the flames appeared to be','Which floor the fire started on and whether you know if anyone is still inside','What subject class was happening when the fire started','The time you last ate before the fire broke out','A firefighter arrives and asks for information. What is the MOST useful thing you can tell them right now?',7,1),(8,'C','The teacher ΓÇö they are your authority in school','Use your own common sense and enter if it looks safe from outside','The firefighter ΓÇö always wait for official fire authority clearance before entering','Either one ΓÇö both have equal authority in this situation','The fire is out. Your teacher says you can re-enter the building. A firefighter says to wait for official clearance. Whose instruction do you follow?',7,1),(9,'C','Keep all lab windows fully open at all times','Avoid doing any experiments that involve heat or chemicals','Never leave heat sources unattended and store flammable materials safely according to lab rules','Install more ceiling lights so the lab is always well lit','Your teacher asks how to prevent lab fires. Which answer is MOST correct?',7,1),(10,'B','Run to find a teacher immediately','Check if the scene is safe, tap shoulders and shout to check response','Start chest compressions immediately without checking anything','Give rescue breaths first then check for pulse','A classmate suddenly collapses in the corridor and is not responding. What is your FIRST action?',7,15),(11,'C','Start CPR and call 108 only after finishing','Wait for someone else to arrive before doing anything','Call 108 on speaker or shout for someone to call, then start CPR immediately','Give only rescue breaths until help arrives','Your classmate is unresponsive and not breathing. You are alone. What do you do next?',7,15),(12,'C','On the left side of the chest directly over the heart','On the upper chest near the collarbone','On the centre of the chest on the lower half of the breastbone','On the stomach just below the ribs','You are about to start chest compressions on an adult. Where exactly do you place your hands?',7,15),(13,'B','Just enough to feel resistance ΓÇö about 1 centimetre','At least 5 centimetres ΓÇö hard and fast','As deep as possible ΓÇö at least 10 centimetres','2 centimetres gently to avoid injury','You are doing compressions. How deep should you press down on an adult\'s chest?',7,15),(14,'C','Press the forehead down and push chin toward chest','Turn the head to the side and open the mouth wide','Tilt the head back and lift the chin upward','Pull the jaw forward without moving the head','After 30 compressions you need to give rescue breaths. What is the correct technique to open the airway?',7,15),(15,'C','Stop CPR immediately ΓÇö something is badly wrong','Slow down to half speed to reduce pressure on the ribs','Continue CPR ΓÇö a cracked rib can happen during correct CPR and is acceptable','Switch to rescue breaths only and stop compressions','You are doing CPR and hear a cracking sound from the chest. What do you do?',7,15),(16,'B','Finish your current set of 30 compressions then put AED away','Use the AED immediately ΓÇö turn it on and follow its voice instructions','Only use AED after CPR has failed for at least 10 minutes','Hand AED to someone else ΓÇö keep doing CPR yourself','An AED machine is brought to you while you are doing CPR. What should you do?',7,15),(17,'B','Continue CPR for 2 more minutes to be safe','Stop CPR, roll them onto their side into recovery position, and keep monitoring their breathing','Give 5 more rescue breaths before stopping','Ask them to stand up and walk to confirm they are okay','The person you were doing CPR on suddenly opens their eyes and starts breathing normally. What do you do?',7,15),(28,'A','Encourage her to cough forcefully','Call an ambulance immediately','Strike her back as hard as possible right away','Give her a large glass of water','A child at a dining table suddenly goes silent, turns red, and clutches her throat. She cannot speak. What do you do first?',25,21),(29,'B','Lay them on the floor and call for help','Switch to five abdominal thrusts','Reach into their mouth to remove the object','Continue back blows for another five rounds','You are performing back blows on a choking adult. After five blows the object has not cleared. What is the next step?',25,21),(30,'C','Continue abdominal thrusts on the unconscious person','Give only rescue breaths with no compressions','Begin CPR and call emergency services immediately','Put them in recovery position and wait','A choking person has gone limp and is now unconscious on the floor. What do you do?',25,21),(31,'D','Call someone immediately and wait for them','Lie on the floor and try to relax','Drink water to wash it down','Thrust your abdomen against the back of a chair or countertop edge','You are alone and feel something stuck in your throat. You cannot cough it out. What do you do?',25,21),(32,'D','Wait for emergency services to arrive','Try to reach into her mouth to remove the object','Back blows only with no thrusts at all','Chest thrusts with hands on the centre of the breastbone','A pregnant woman is choking and you cannot wrap your arms around her abdomen for thrusts. What do you use instead?',25,21),(33,'B','Immediately begin abdominal thrusts','Encourage them to keep coughing and do not intervene yet','Deliver five back blows right away','Call an ambulance and wait for them','A person is choking but is still coughing loudly and producing sound. What is the correct action?',25,21),(34,'D','Continue three more thrusts to be completely sure','Give them water immediately to soothe the throat','Nothing else is needed once the object is out','Check breathing and arrange medical evaluation for possible internal injury','You deliver abdominal thrusts to an adult. After the third thrust a piece of food flies out of their mouth. What do you do next?',25,21),(35,'C','Upright in a sitting position for small abdominal thrusts','Hold them upright while calling an ambulance','Face down along your forearm for back blows then face up on your thigh for chest thrusts','Lay them flat on the floor for infant CPR','An infant under one year old appears to be choking and cannot cry or breathe. How do you position them?',25,21),(36,'D','Immediately perform abdominal thrusts to dislodge it','Deliver five back blows right away','Give water to try to wash the marble further down','Call emergency services immediately and keep the child calm without performing thrusts','A child swallowed a small marble and is now breathing with a loud high-pitched noise but can still breathe. What do you do?',25,21),(37,'C','On the centre of the chest over the heart','On the lower abdomen near the hips','Just above the navel and well below the breastbone','Anywhere firmly on the upper stomach area','A bystander says your hand position for abdominal thrusts is wrong. Where exactly should your fist be?',25,21),(38,'C','Call emergency services before approaching the pool','Throw a rope and wait for them to grab it','Lift them out immediately, check breathing, start CPR if not breathing','Jump in the water immediately without checking depth','You see a child floating face down in a swimming pool not moving. No one else is around. What do you do first?',25,22),(39,'B','Jump in to swim to them immediately','Throw any floating object you can find ΓÇö life ring, rope, pool noodle','Shout instructions to them from shore','Call emergency services and wait','A person in the ocean appears to be in trouble ΓÇö head low, mouth at water level, not waving. What should you do first?',25,22),(40,'D','30 chest compressions first same as standard CPR','Recovery position only and wait','Tip her upside down to drain water first','Two rescue breaths then 30 chest compressions','You pull a drowned teenager out of a pool. She is unresponsive and not breathing. What do you start with?',25,22),(41,'C','Fight them off and swim away','Try to hold them above water by force','Take a deep breath, go under briefly ΓÇö the person will release to try to surface','Shout to the crowd and wait for help','A drowning person grabs you as you try to rescue them and begins pulling you under. What do you do?',25,22),(42,'D','Give them rest and see if it passes overnight','Give them water to drink to clear the cough','Wait until tomorrow morning and reassess','Take them to hospital immediately ΓÇö these are secondary drowning symptoms','A child who was rescued from a pool three hours ago is now coughing persistently and seems very tired. What do you do?',25,22),(43,'B','Jump in immediately ΓÇö he will drown otherwise','Row out with a boat if available before entering the water','Wait for emergency services only','Throw heavy objects near him to create waves','A man is floating face down in a river and not moving. You have a rope but cannot reach him. What is the next option?',25,22),(44,'D','Stop CPR immediately','Continue CPR without pausing at all','Put them in recovery position and stop CPR permanently','Turn their head to the side, clear the airway, then continue CPR','You are performing CPR on a drowning victim and they vomit. What do you do?',25,22),(45,'D','Give them cold water to drink','Leave them to rest on the ground','Only treat visible injuries and ignore the cold','Keep them warm and take them to hospital immediately','A person was rescued from flooding and is breathing but very cold and confused. What is the priority?',25,22),(46,'D','Wait for emergency services to arrive','Perform CPR for 2 minutes then stop to call again','Get help from others first before starting CPR','Begin CPR immediately and keep going until services arrive','You are the only person present when someone drowns. Emergency services are 10 minutes away. What do you do?',25,22),(47,'C','Call emergency services before touching the child','Throw a floating toy and encourage them to grab it','Lift them out immediately, check breathing, and start CPR if not breathing','Wait to see if they float naturally','A toddler has fallen into a garden pond and is face down. What do you do immediately?',25,22),(48,'A','Turn around ΓÇö never drive into floodwater of unknown depth','Drive slowly through the centre of the road','Drive through quickly to minimise time in water','Get out of the car and wade to check depth first','You are driving and come to a road covered with water of unknown depth. What do you do?',25,23),(49,'B','Try the door handle repeatedly until it opens','Use a hard object to break the corner of the window and escape','Call emergency services and wait inside the car','Move to the back seat away from the water','Your car is flooding rapidly ΓÇö water is at door level and the electric windows have stopped working. What do you do?',25,23),(50,'C','Go to the basement away from the rising water','Stay on the ground floor near the door','Move to the roof with a tool to signal rescuers ΓÇö do not enter a closed attic','Try to drive away through the floodwater','You are in a single-storey house and floodwater is rising rapidly outside. What is the safest immediate action?',25,23),(51,'D','Walk through the water to move the power line to safety','Call the electricity company and continue walking','Check if the line is sparking before warning others','Shout a warning immediately and keep everyone at least 10 metres away','You see a downed power line lying in standing floodwater. People are standing nearby unaware. What do you do?',25,23),(52,'A','Grab only pre-packed emergency items and leave immediately','30 minutes to collect important documents and valuables','1 hour ΓÇö evacuation orders are rarely enforced strictly','Wait until the flood water actually reaches your street','An evacuation order has been issued for your area due to flooding. You want to collect more items first. What is acceptable?',25,23),(53,'D','Enter immediately to prevent theft of your belongings','Enter if the water has fully receded from the ground floor','Enter to photograph damage for insurance before cleaning up','Wait for official clearance from authorities before entering','Floodwater has receded completely. You want to enter your home. What do you do first?',25,23),(54,'B','Wade through quickly holding your belongings above water','Do not enter ΓÇö use a stick to test depth and find an alternative route','Wade through slowly while holding onto a wall or fence','Only wade through if a companion is with you','You are on foot and floodwater on the road is about 20 cm deep and moving slowly. What should you do?',25,23),(55,'D','Keep and use them ΓÇö tins are fully waterproof always','Wash the tins thoroughly and use the food inside','Boil the contents before eating them','Discard them ΓÇö floodwater contamination can enter through seals that appear intact','After a flood you find tinned food cans that were submerged. The seals appear intact. What do you do?',25,23),(56,'C','A laptop connected to any available WiFi network','A television for emergency news updates','Battery-powered or hand-crank emergency radio for official broadcasts','Signal mirrors to attract passing aircraft','Your mobile phone has lost signal in a flood affected area. What communication device should you rely on?',25,23),(57,'C','Swim hard against the current toward the nearest bank','Grab the first solid object you see and hold on tightly','Float on your back with feet pointing downstream to kick off obstacles','Dive underwater and crawl along the bottom to the bank','You are caught in fast-moving floodwater on foot and cannot stand. What is the survival technique?',25,23),(58,'A','Drop under the desk, hold on, and cover your head and neck','Run for the nearest exit immediately','Stand in the nearest doorframe','Crouch near the exterior window wall','An earthquake begins while you are sitting at your office desk. The shaking is strong. What do you do immediately?',25,24),(59,'B','Run into the nearest building for shelter immediately','Move away from buildings into open space and drop to the ground','Stand against a building wall for protection from falling objects','Run along the street parallel to the buildings','You are outdoors in a city when an earthquake starts. There are tall buildings on both sides of the street. What do you do?',25,24),(60,'D','Return home to check for structural damage','Go to the beach to watch for any tsunami wave','Wait for an official warning before deciding to move','Move to high ground immediately ΓÇö a tsunami may follow within minutes','The shaking has stopped and you are near the coast. What is your immediate next action?',25,24),(61,'C','Open all windows to ventilate the smell safely','Light a candle to see the extent of the damage','Leave immediately, leave the door open, and call the gas company from outside','Turn on the main electrical switch to check if it is working','After the earthquake you smell a strong gas odour in your home. What do you do?',25,24),(62,'C','Run immediately for the staircase to evacuate','Take the elevator to the ground floor quickly','Get against an interior wall and cover your head with your arms','Stand in the elevator door frame for structural support','You are on the 8th floor of an office building when the earthquake strikes. There is no desk nearby. What do you do?',25,24),(63,'D','Go outside now since the main quake has already passed','Walk around to assess how bad the crack is','Call someone to report the crack while standing still','Take cover immediately ΓÇö the building may be further damaged by aftershocks','The main earthquake has passed but a strong aftershock hits and part of the ceiling has cracked. What do you do?',25,24),(64,'D','Shout continuously without stopping to guide them','Try to dig yourself out toward the sound of rescuers','Keep your phone torch on continuously to save the battery','Tap on a pipe or wall rhythmically at regular intervals to guide rescuers','You are trapped under a collapsed section of a building and can hear rescuers working nearby. What do you do?',25,24),(65,'C','Good idea ΓÇö running outside is always safer in an earthquake','Only run if the shaking lasts more than 30 seconds','Stop ΓÇö most injuries happen near exits from falling debris ΓÇö drop and take cover here','Run only if there is a completely clear path to the exit','A co-worker attempts to run outside during the shaking. What do you tell them?',25,24),(66,'D','Go quickly and come back out within two minutes','Only go back if the building looks completely undamaged from outside','Wait exactly 30 minutes then it is safe to re-enter','Do not re-enter ΓÇö buildings may be structurally unsafe after an earthquake','After evacuating a building following an earthquake a colleague wants to go back inside to retrieve her bag. What do you advise?',25,24),(67,'D','Duck behind the display shelf for protection from falling debris','Run toward the mall exit along the shop fronts','Stand in the nearest shop doorframe for protection','Move away from the shelf and drop to the floor covering your head','An earthquake strikes while you are in a shopping mall. There is a large display shelf nearby. What do you do?',25,24),(68,'A','Press the emergency alarm button and call building security','Force the doors open and climb out to safety','Jump repeatedly to trigger the safety brake system','Climb through the ceiling hatch to the top','The elevator you are in suddenly stops between floors with a jolt. Lights are still on. What do you do first?',25,25),(69,'B','Stay in the elevator until the alarm stops sounding','Press the nearest floor button, exit when doors open, then take stairs','Press the ground floor button immediately to evacuate','Press the emergency stop button and wait for rescue','You are in an elevator when the fire alarm sounds. You are currently on the 7th floor. What do you do?',25,25),(70,'C','Try to pry the doors open immediately before power returns','Climb through the ceiling hatch and shimmy down the cable','Stay calm, press the alarm, and wait for trained rescue technicians','Jump repeatedly hoping to land on a nearby floor level','The power cuts out while you are in the elevator. It stops suddenly and emergency lighting activates. What do you do?',25,25),(71,'D','Jump just before it hits the bottom to reduce impact force','Stand in the corner and hold the railing tightly','Crouch down with your head between your knees','Press all floor buttons immediately and lie flat on the floor covering your head','You feel the elevator moving abnormally fast downward and all attempts to stop it have failed. What do you do?',25,25),(72,'A','Press the alarm, cover the door gap with clothing, and call emergency services','Force the door open to escape the smoke immediately','Press all buttons rapidly to reach any floor as fast as possible','Crouch on the floor and wait for the smoke to clear on its own','You smell smoke entering the elevator cabin from the door gap. You are stuck between floors. What do you do?',25,25),(73,'D','Pull the child hard to free them from the doors quickly','Press the emergency stop button only and wait','Press any random button to move the elevator so doors open','Press the door open button immediately and use manual open if available','A child is trapped with their fingers caught in the closing elevator doors. What do you do immediately?',25,25),(74,'D','Step carefully into the elevated cabin ΓÇö it is close enough','Jump up into the cabin as the gap is manageable','Use it only for going down not up as it is safer','Do not use this elevator and report it to building management immediately','You enter a building and find the elevator cabin floor is 20 cm above the building floor level. What do you do?',25,25),(75,'D','Post on social media so others can call for help','Keep the torch on to feel less scared in the dark','Call all family members to inform them of your location','Call 112 emergency services or building security then conserve the battery','You have been trapped in an elevator for 20 minutes. Your phone has only 10% battery left. What is the priority use?',25,25),(76,'D','Help them up through the hatch as it is the fastest escape','Let them decide since you are not a trained technician','Only allow it if the elevator is very close to a floor level','Firmly advise against it ΓÇö the shaft has moving counterweights and deadly electrical cables','A person in the elevator is panicking and wants to climb through the roof hatch to escape between floors. What do you do?',25,25),(77,'D','There is no risk if the gap is less than 30 centimetres','The risk only applies to elderly or disabled passengers','The elevator will automatically realign if you simply wait','You may fall into the gap between the cabin and the floor and be seriously injured','The elevator doors open but the cabin floor is well below the landing level. What is the risk of stepping out?',25,25),(78,'A','Move immediately to high ground without waiting for any warning','Stay and watch the ocean carefully for any visible signs','Go back to your hotel and turn on the news first','Call family members to warn them before you move','You are on a beach and feel a strong earthquake lasting about 30 seconds. There is no official warning yet. What do you do?',25,26),(79,'D','Walk down to see the interesting natural phenomenon','Take photographs quickly before leaving the area','Wait to officially confirm with authorities before acting','Shout a warning loudly and run to high ground immediately ΓÇö drawback means a wave is coming','You notice the ocean has rapidly receded and tourists nearby are walking onto the exposed seafloor. What do you do?',25,26),(80,'D','Go outside immediately to check the damage and help others','Move to the ground floor to prepare for a quick evacuation','The danger is completely over ΓÇö go assess your property now','Stay on the upper floors ΓÇö more waves will come for hours, do not go outside','The first tsunami wave has struck and receded. Your building is damaged but still standing. What do you do?',25,26),(81,'D','Swim out further to deeper sea ΓÇö waves are smaller in deep water','Stay where you are and tread water through the incoming waves','Float on your back and wait for the wave to pass over you','Swim as fast as possible toward shore and run inland immediately','You are swimming in the ocean when a tsunami warning is announced on loudspeakers on shore. What do you do?',25,26),(82,'C','Swim as hard as possible against the current toward the nearest bank','Dive below the wave surface to avoid the force above','Look for something to hold onto to float and protect your head from debris','Lie flat and let the wave roll completely over you','A tsunami wave catches you before you can escape. You cannot fight the current. What do you do?',25,26),(83,'D','Go to the ground floor and run inland as fast as possible','Drive immediately away from the coast by car','Stand on the hotel roof to be visible to rescue helicopters','Stay on the upper floors of this building ΓÇö it is a tall reinforced concrete structure','You are in a coastal city and receive an official tsunami warning. You are on the 12th floor of a reinforced concrete hotel. What do you do?',25,26),(84,'D','Yes ΓÇö eight hours is more than enough time for all waves to pass','Yes ΓÇö only the very first wave is ever dangerous in any tsunami','Yes ΓÇö if no additional wave has come in the past two hours','No ΓÇö tsunami waves can continue for up to eight hours and the threat remains until official clearance','Eight hours after the first tsunami wave officials have not yet issued an all-clear. Is it safe to return to the beach?',25,26),(85,'D','Jump into the water and swim toward the nearest shore','Break a window and hold onto the exterior wall of the building','Stay on the second floor and hold on tightly to a fixed structure','Move to the roof immediately and signal rescuers ΓÇö water may not reach the roof level','A tsunami surge has trapped you on the second floor of a building with no higher floors available. Water is still rising. What do you do?',25,26),(86,'D','Gather all family members first even if it takes an extra 10 minutes','Pack all essential documents before leaving the house','Check social media first to confirm the warning is genuine','Begin evacuation immediately without any delay ΓÇö every second counts','Your family evacuation plan takes 25 minutes to reach high ground. A tsunami warning has just been issued. What do you do?',25,26),(87,'D','Enter carefully and assess the damage yourself thoroughly','Enter immediately since the tsunami danger is now completely over','Only enter if none of the main walls have visibly collapsed','Have it inspected by a structural engineer before entering ΓÇö it may collapse without warning','After a tsunami officials declare it safe to return. You find your home has structural cracks in the walls. What do you do?',25,26),(88,'A','Check for injuries, cover your mouth, and tap on pipes rhythmically to signal rescuers','Shout continuously without stopping to guide them to you','Try to immediately dig your way out toward the sound','Light your phone torch and search actively for an exit path','A large earthquake has struck and you are trapped under debris with rescuers working nearby. What do you do first?',25,27),(89,'B','Yes ΓÇö they are very close to the entrance so it is safe enough','No ΓÇö stay outside, call emergency services, and talk calmly to keep them conscious','Yes ΓÇö you have a moral duty to help immediately','Only enter if no secondary collapse sound has been heard for 5 full minutes','You are a bystander at a building collapse and can see someone trapped just inside the entrance. Do you enter?',25,27),(90,'D','Seal the cracks with plaster and continue using the building normally','Only be concerned if the cracks visibly grow wider over time','Report to the landlord and continue using the building as normal','Evacuate immediately and report to a structural engineer ΓÇö these are serious collapse warning signs','You notice diagonal cracks at window corners and the door to a room no longer closes after recent heavy rains. What do you do?',25,27),(91,'D','Shout as loudly and continuously as possible without pause','Use your phone torch to flash repeatedly in any direction','Try to move debris to make yourself visible from above','Tap on a metal pipe or concrete in sets of three ΓÇö this conserves air and carries further than shouting','You are trapped under rubble and can hear rescue workers but they are still far away. What is the best signalling method?',25,27),(92,'D','Rescuers should speed up to finish the rescue before conditions worsen','Only rescuers near exposed windows should immediately exit','Continue working if the aftershock appears to be small in magnitude','All rescuers evacuate the structure immediately ΓÇö aftershocks cause secondary collapse killing rescuers','An aftershock hits while rescue workers are actively working in a partially collapsed building near you. What should happen?',25,27),(93,'D','Yes ΓÇö use it very briefly to quickly check your immediate surroundings','Only if the gas smell seems faint rather than strong','Yes if no gas company warning signs are visible in the area','Absolutely not ΓÇö a single spark can ignite a gas leak and cause a deadly explosion','You smell gas after a building collapse. You have a lighter with you to see in the complete darkness. Should you use it?',25,27),(94,'D','Drink it all immediately to maintain maximum physical strength','Avoid drinking entirely ΓÇö water will make you need to urinate','Pour it on your face to stay cool and alert','Drink small amounts at regular intervals to extend your survival time','You have been trapped under rubble for several hours and have a small bottle of water. What should you do with it?',25,27),(95,'C','Dig carefully from the opposite side of the building','Help if you wear a hard hat for basic protection','Leave all rescue to trained teams ΓÇö untrained digging can trigger secondary collapse and harm survivors','Dig only with bare hands to avoid damaging any survivors','Rescue teams arrive at a collapse scene. A family member of a trapped person wants to help dig manually. What should they be told?',25,27),(96,'D','Enter carefully to check if it is actually structurally safe inside','Photograph it and post online to alert the community','Only take action if it has visibly moved even further since you first noticed','Alert authorities and evacuate the entire surrounding area immediately','You see a building with a severe visible lean that was not there yesterday. What is the correct action?',25,27),(97,'D','Use the GPS app to precisely determine your location coordinates','Use the torch to look carefully for any possible exit route','Send a text message to all family members simultaneously','Call 112 ΓÇö this works without a SIM and will relay your location to emergency services','A phone without a SIM card has only 5% battery remaining. You are completely trapped. What is the single most important use?',25,27),(98,'A','Raise your arms to the boxer stance and move diagonally toward the edge of the crowd','Push back hard against the crowd flow to create space around you','Shout loudly at the people around you to stop pushing','Crouch down low to avoid the pressure from above','You are at a crowded concert and feel the crowd begin to surge and push hard. You can barely move your arms. What do you do first?',25,28),(99,'D','The crowd is enjoying the event enthusiastically in a wave','Security personnel are moving through the crowd on routine patrol','A celebrity is moving through the crowd unexpectedly','A surge is occurring ahead ΓÇö start moving toward the nearest exit edge immediately','You see a ripple effect moving through the crowd ahead of you at a large festival. What does this mean?',25,28),(100,'C','Bend down quickly and pick it up before the crowd moves over it','Stop completely and ask people around you to make space','Leave it ΓÇö bending down in a dense crowd means you may not be able to stand again','Call out to people nearby to help you retrieve it safely','You drop your phone in a very dense moving crowd. What do you do?',25,28),(101,'B','Lie completely flat on your back with arms stretched wide','Curl on your side with knees to chest, cover your head, face the direction of crowd movement','Stand up immediately at any cost before anyone steps on you','Roll rapidly in any direction away from the crowd','You fall to the ground in a stampede. What position do you take immediately?',25,28),(102,'B','Push back as hard as you can against the crowd behind you','Raise your arms in boxer stance and shout to security at the barrier for help','Crouch down below the pressure level of the crowd','Wait calmly for the crowd to naturally thin out on its own','You are near the front of a concert crowd pressed hard against the barrier. You are having difficulty breathing. What do you do?',25,28),(103,'D','Move toward the screaming to see what is happening and help','Stay completely still and wait for an official announcement','Take out your phone and start filming to document the incident','Move immediately away from the direction of the screaming toward the nearest exit','You hear sudden screaming from a direction you cannot see at a religious gathering. What do you do?',25,28),(104,'D','Find the best central spot with the clearest view of the stage','Register your attendance with the nearest security personnel','Locate the food and water stations for later in the event','Identify the two nearest exits ΓÇö not just the main entrance you entered through','You are entering a large outdoor concert with thousands of people. What is the very first thing you should do?',25,28),(105,'D','Stay for the full event ΓÇö you paid for the ticket','Move toward the centre where there is more space','Wait 30 more minutes to see if it gets better on its own','Leave early now ΓÇö sensing dangerous density is the right time to exit before pressure peaks','The crowd at an event is getting increasingly dense and uncomfortable around you. The event has 2 more hours. What do you do?',25,28),(106,'D','Stay in the survival position until the entire crowd fully passes','Roll toward the nearest wall before attempting to stand','Call out for help and wait for someone to physically pull you up','Push up on all fours immediately then stand quickly during the gap','You have fallen in a stampede and managed to curl into the survival position. A brief gap appears in the crowd flow. What do you do?',25,28),(107,'D','Install comprehensive security cameras throughout the entire venue','Hire the maximum number of security guards affordable','Ensure there is enough food and water for all attendees throughout','Clearly mark multiple separate entry and exit routes and assign trained crowd monitors at each','You are organising a school event for 500 students. What is the single most important safety measure to implement?',25,28),(108,'A','Leave immediately with your emergency kit following the official evacuation route','Stay home since your house is built from concrete','Leave in the morning when traffic will be lighter','Wait to see if the forecast track changes overnight','A very severe cyclone is forecast to make landfall near your coastal city in 24 hours and an evacuation order is issued. What do you do?',25,29),(109,'D','The cyclone has completely passed and it is now safe to go outside','The cyclone has weakened significantly and will not return','This is a normal break and the storm will resume only weakly','The eye is passing over ΓÇö stay inside as the back eyewall will hit with equal force','You are sheltering indoors during a cyclone and the wind suddenly stops completely and the sky clears. What does this mean?',25,29),(110,'D','Yes ΓÇö open windows reduce internal pressure and protect the roof structure','Yes ΓÇö but only if you are on the ground floor of the building','Yes ΓÇö only if wind speed is confirmed below severe category level','No ΓÇö open windows allow wind inside creating dangerous uplift that can blow off the roof','You want to open a window slightly during a cyclone to equalise pressure inside. Should you?',25,29),(111,'D','Open all windows to let the surge water flow freely through','Drive your car immediately to higher ground outside','Go outside and try to reach a neighbour house on higher ground','Move to the highest point in your home and signal for rescue ΓÇö do not go outside into the surge','Storm surge from the cyclone is entering your single-storey coastal home. What do you do?',25,29),(112,'D','Check if the line is actively sparking before deciding whether to approach','Step carefully around all the puddles and pass by the line quickly','Move the line safely using a dry wooden stick to clear the road','Assume the line is live, stay far away, and report it to authorities immediately','After the cyclone you see a downed power line on your street with puddles of water nearby. What do you do?',25,29),(113,'C','Shelter under the largest and strongest nearby tree','Stand against the tree trunk on the sheltered side','Move away from all trees, find a low ditch, and lie flat covering your head','Stand under the nearest highway overpass bridge structure','You are caught outdoors during a cyclone and cannot reach any shelter. Trees are the only nearby cover. What do you do?',25,29),(114,'D','Pack all entertainment items for the sheltering period ahead','Cook and consume all food currently in the refrigerator first','Charge your devices and continue normal daily activities','Board up windows and fill all available containers with clean water','IMD has issued a cyclone warning and you have 6 hours before expected landfall. What is your very first priority action?',25,29),(115,'D','Boil it for one minute and then use it normally for all purposes','Use it for washing and cleaning but not for drinking or cooking','It is safe once the strange smell fades after a few minutes','Do not use it at all ΓÇö use only bottled water until authorities issue official clearance','During cyclone cleanup your tap water has a strange colour and unusual smell. What do you do?',25,29),(116,'D','Only for a few seconds while holding tightly onto your hand','Only if they wear a protective helmet and hold onto something fixed','Only if the wind speed is confirmed to be below severe level','Absolutely not ΓÇö wind projectiles and surge conditions are lethal outside during any severe cyclone','A child in your shelter wants to go outside briefly just to see the cyclone winds. What do you tell them?',25,29),(117,'D','Leave it and focus entirely on your personal evacuation preparations','Park it inside the garage and close the door securely','Tie it firmly to the nearest tree to prevent it from floating away','Move it to higher ground immediately before storm surge or flooding arrives','Your vehicle is parked in a low-lying coastal area with a cyclone approaching in 12 hours. What do you do?',25,29);
