/*!40000 ALTER TABLE `education_content` DISABLE KEYS */;
INSERT INTO `education_content` VALUES (68,'{\"paragraph\":\"Fire is a rapid chemical reaction that produces heat, light, and smoke. In a school or college, fires can start from electrical short circuits in labs, unattended candles or gas burners, overloaded power sockets, or improper disposal of flammable materials like chemicals and paper. The three things a fire always needs to keep burning are fuel, oxygen, and heat ΓÇö known as the fire triangle. Remove any one of these three and the fire stops. A water extinguisher removes heat. A CO2 extinguisher removes oxygen. Cutting off fuel means removing the burning material. Understanding this principle is the foundation of all fire safety knowledge.\",\"question\":\"What are the three things that form the fire triangle ΓÇö all of which a fire needs to keep burning?\",\"options\":[\"Wood, Air, Spark\",\"Fuel, Oxygen, Heat\",\"Smoke, Heat, Light\",\"Gas, Electricity, Paper\"],\"answer\":\"Fuel, Oxygen, Heat\"}',1,1),(69,'{\"paragraph\":\"The most important thing when you discover a fire is to stay calm and raise the alarm immediately. Shout FIRE loudly to alert everyone nearby, activate the nearest fire alarm pull station if available, and call the fire emergency number ΓÇö 101 in India. Never try to fight a large or growing fire by yourself. Your absolute first priority is always to alert others and begin evacuation. Every second spent alerting people saves more lives than any individual attempt to fight the fire. If the fire is very small, like a wastepaper bin fire, a single person with the right extinguisher can handle it, but only if they have been trained and the fire is contained.\",\"question\":\"What is the FIRST thing you must do when you discover a fire ΓÇö before anything else?\",\"options\":[\"Try to put it out with water\",\"Collect your important belongings first\",\"Stay calm and raise the alarm immediately\",\"Hide in the nearest toilet until help arrives\"],\"answer\":\"Stay calm and raise the alarm immediately\"}',1,2),(70,'{\"paragraph\":\"When evacuating a building during a fire, always use the stairs ΓÇö never use a lift or elevator, because power may cut out and trap you inside. Smoke rises to ceiling level first, so if there is heavy smoke in a corridor, get low and crawl under the smoke where the air is cleaner and you can still breathe. Before opening any door during a fire, always touch it with the back of your hand near the top of the door. If it feels hot, do not open it ΓÇö fire or superheated gases are likely on the other side. If the door is cool, open it slowly and carefully while staying behind it as a shield.\",\"question\":\"Why should you touch a door with the BACK of your hand ΓÇö not your palm ΓÇö before opening it during a fire?\",\"options\":[\"It is easier to push the door open that way\",\"A burn on the back of the hand heals faster than on the palm\",\"The back of the hand is more sensitive to heat so you detect danger without grabbing\",\"It is just a tradition with no real reason\"],\"answer\":\"The back of the hand is more sensitive to heat so you detect danger without grabbing\"}',1,3),(71,'{\"paragraph\":\"Fire extinguishers are the first line of defence against small, contained fires. There are four main types: Red water extinguishers for wood, paper, and fabric fires. CO2 carbon dioxide extinguishers for electrical fires ΓÇö NEVER use water on electrical fires as it conducts electricity and can cause electrocution. Dry powder extinguishers for flammable liquid and gas fires. Foam extinguishers for burning liquids. Always remember the word PASS when using a fire extinguisher: Pull the pin at the top. Aim the nozzle at the BASE of the fire, not the flames. Squeeze the handle. Sweep side to side until the fire is out or the extinguisher is empty.\",\"question\":\"What does the word PASS stand for when using a fire extinguisher?\",\"options\":[\"Push, Aim, Spray, Stop\",\"Pull, Aim, Squeeze, Sweep\",\"Prepare, Alert, Spray, Secure\",\"Point, Activate, Spray, Step back\"],\"answer\":\"Pull, Aim, Squeeze, Sweep\"}',1,4),(72,'{\"paragraph\":\"If your clothes catch fire, the single most dangerous thing you can do is run ΓÇö because running fans the flames with oxygen and makes the fire burn hotter and faster across more of your clothing. Instead, immediately stop what you are doing, drop to the ground to prevent flames rising toward your face, and roll back and forth to smother the fire by cutting off its oxygen. This is called Stop, Drop and Roll. If someone else is on fire near you, help them drop and roll, or wrap them quickly and tightly in a heavy blanket, coat, or curtain to cut off the oxygen supply. After the fire on clothing is out, cool the burnt skin with cool ΓÇö not cold ΓÇö running water for a minimum of 10 minutes. Never apply ice, butter, toothpaste, or oil to burns.\",\"question\":\"When your clothes catch fire, why is running the WORST thing you can do?\",\"options\":[\"You will trip and fall\",\"Running increases oxygen to the fire, making it burn faster and hotter\",\"Running will spread the fire to other people\",\"Running delays the burning and is actually helpful\"],\"answer\":\"Running increases oxygen to the fire, making it burn faster and hotter\"}',1,5),(73,'{\"paragraph\":\"After escaping a building fire, never go back inside for any reason ΓÇö not for friends, not for your phone or bag, and not for pets. Conditions inside a burning building can change fatally within seconds ΓÇö a corridor that was clear moments ago may now be filled with toxic smoke or engulfed in flames. Proceed immediately to the designated assembly point, which is a safe open area away from the building, and wait there. Help firefighters by giving accurate information: which floor the fire started on, what caused it if known, and whether anyone is still inside. Never re-enter the building until a firefighter officially and clearly tells you it is safe to do so.\",\"question\":\"After safely escaping a fire, when is it safe to go back into the building?\",\"options\":[\"After waiting 10 minutes outside\",\"When the smoke coming from windows stops completely\",\"When a firefighter officially declares the building safe\",\"When you can no longer see flames from outside\"],\"answer\":\"When a firefighter officially declares the building safe\"}',1,6),(80,'{\"paragraph\":\"CPR stands for Cardiopulmonary Resuscitation. It is a life-saving emergency procedure performed when a person\'s heart has stopped beating or they have stopped breathing. CPR combines chest compressions with rescue breaths to manually pump blood through the body and deliver oxygen to the brain and vital organs. Without CPR, brain cells begin to die within 4 to 6 minutes of the heart stopping. With CPR started immediately, a person\'s chance of survival can double or even triple. CPR can be performed by anyone ΓÇö you do not need to be a doctor. Learning it is one of the most important skills a student can have.\",\"question\":\"What does CPR stand for?\",\"options\":[\"Critical Patient Response\",\"Cardiopulmonary Resuscitation\",\"Cardiac Pressure Revival\",\"Chest and Pulse Recovery\"],\"answer\":\"Cardiopulmonary Resuscitation\"}',15,1),(81,'{\"paragraph\":\"Before starting CPR, you must first check that the scene is safe for you to approach ΓÇö never put yourself in danger. Then check the person: tap their shoulders firmly and shout loudly asking if they are okay. If there is no response, shout for someone nearby to call emergency services ΓÇö 108 in India for ambulance. If you are alone, call 108 yourself before starting CPR if possible, or use the speakerphone. Then check for breathing by looking at the chest for rise and fall for no more than 10 seconds. If the person is not breathing normally or only gasping, begin CPR immediately.\",\"question\":\"What is the emergency ambulance number to call in India before starting CPR?\",\"options\":[\"100\",\"101\",\"108\",\"104\"],\"answer\":\"108\"}',15,2),(82,'{\"paragraph\":\"Chest compressions are the most important part of CPR. Place the heel of one hand on the centre of the person\'s chest ΓÇö on the lower half of the breastbone called the sternum. Place your other hand on top and interlock your fingers. Keep your arms straight and press down hard and fast. Compressions must be at least 5 centimetres deep ΓÇö about 2 inches ΓÇö for an adult. The rate is 100 to 120 compressions per minute, which is roughly the beat of the song Stayin Alive by the Bee Gees. Allow the chest to fully rise back up between each compression ΓÇö this is called chest recoil and it is essential for blood to refill the heart.\",\"question\":\"How deep must each chest compression be for an adult during CPR?\",\"options\":[\"1 centimetre\",\"2 centimetres\",\"At least 5 centimetres\",\"10 centimetres\"],\"answer\":\"At least 5 centimetres\"}',15,3),(83,'{\"paragraph\":\"Rescue breaths deliver oxygen into the person\'s lungs. To give a rescue breath, tilt the person\'s head back gently and lift the chin to open the airway. Pinch the nose shut with your fingers, make a complete seal over their mouth with your mouth, and breathe in steadily for about 1 second while watching the chest rise. Give 2 rescue breaths after every 30 chest compressions. This 30 compressions to 2 breaths ratio is the standard adult CPR cycle. If you are not trained or not comfortable giving rescue breaths, hands-only CPR with continuous chest compressions is still very effective and better than doing nothing.\",\"question\":\"What is the correct ratio of chest compressions to rescue breaths in adult CPR?\",\"options\":[\"15 compressions to 1 breath\",\"30 compressions to 2 breaths\",\"20 compressions to 2 breaths\",\"50 compressions to 1 breath\"],\"answer\":\"30 compressions to 2 breaths\"}',15,4),(84,'{\"paragraph\":\"CPR for children aged 1 to puberty is slightly different from adult CPR. Use only one hand or two fingers for compressions on a small child, and compress about 5 centimetres or one third of the chest depth. For infants under 1 year old, use only two fingers on the centre of the chest just below the nipple line, and compress about 4 centimetres. Give gentler rescue breaths for both ΓÇö just enough to see the chest rise. The ratio of 30 compressions to 2 breaths remains the same for one rescuer. If two rescuers are present for an infant, use 15 compressions to 2 breaths. Always start CPR with 5 initial rescue breaths for children and infants before beginning compressions.\",\"question\":\"For an infant under 1 year old, how many fingers should be used for chest compressions during CPR?\",\"options\":[\"Full hand with all fingers\",\"One hand heel only\",\"Two fingers\",\"Three fingers\"],\"answer\":\"Two fingers\"}',15,5),(85,'{\"paragraph\":\"Continue CPR without stopping until one of these happens: the person starts breathing normally on their own, a trained medical professional arrives and takes over, an Automated External Defibrillator (AED) is brought and ready to use, or you are physically too exhausted to continue. If an AED is available, use it as soon as possible ΓÇö it will give you voice instructions and will deliver a controlled electric shock to restart the heart if needed. Never feel bad about the outcome ΓÇö any CPR attempt gives a person a chance they would not have had otherwise. Bystander CPR saves thousands of lives every year. The most important thing is that you tried.\",\"question\":\"When should you stop performing CPR?\",\"options\":[\"After exactly 5 minutes regardless of the situation\",\"When the person looks uncomfortable\",\"When the person breathes normally, a medical professional takes over, or an AED is ready\",\"After 30 cycles of 30 compressions and 2 breaths\"],\"answer\":\"When the person breathes normally, a medical professional takes over, or an AED is ready\"}',15,6),(96,'{\"paragraph\":\"Choking occurs when a foreign object such as a small toy, a piece of hard candy, or a chunk of food becomes lodged in the throat or windpipe, partially or completely blocking the airway. The airway is a narrow passage and even a small obstruction can prevent oxygen from reaching the lungs. Children under five are at the highest risk because they explore objects with their mouths and have smaller airways than adults. Recognising choking early and acting immediately is the difference between life and death.\",\"question\":\"What is choking?\",\"options\":[\"A blocked airway caused by a foreign object\",\"A sudden drop in blood pressure\",\"A heart attack\",\"An allergic reaction to food\"],\"answer\":\"A blocked airway caused by a foreign object\"}',21,0),(97,'{\"paragraph\":\"You can recognise choking by these signs: the person cannot speak or can only whisper, they cannot breathe or produce a high-pitched noise while breathing, they cannot cough effectively, their lips or fingernails may turn blue which is called cyanosis, and they instinctively clutch their throat with one or both hands. This gesture of hands at the throat is the universal choking signal recognised worldwide by first responders and bystanders alike. If you see this sign act immediately without hesitation.\",\"question\":\"What is the universal sign of choking?\",\"options\":[\"Holding the stomach\",\"Hands clutching the throat\",\"Waving both arms\",\"Lying flat on the ground\"],\"answer\":\"Hands clutching the throat\"}',21,1),(98,'{\"paragraph\":\"If the choking person can still cough forcefully, encourage them to keep coughing. A strong cough creates far more pressure than any external technique and may dislodge the object on its own. Do not interfere while effective coughing continues. Only act if the cough becomes silent, breathing stops, or the person loses the ability to make any sound. These are signs the airway is fully blocked and the situation is now life-threatening requiring immediate physical intervention.\",\"question\":\"What should you do if a choking person can still cough forcefully?\",\"options\":[\"Call an ambulance immediately\",\"Give them water to drink\",\"Immediately perform back blows\",\"Encourage them to keep coughing\"],\"answer\":\"Encourage them to keep coughing\"}',21,2),(99,'{\"paragraph\":\"If coughing fails, perform five firm back blows. Stand slightly behind the person, support their chest with one hand, and lean them forward so their head is lower than their chest. Use the heel of your other hand to deliver five sharp blows between the shoulder blades. Each blow should be a separate distinct strike. After every five blows check whether the blockage has cleared by looking in the mouth. If the object is visible remove it. If not, move immediately to abdominal thrusts.\",\"question\":\"Where do you deliver back blows during choking first aid?\",\"options\":[\"On the lower back\",\"On the chest\",\"Between the shoulder blades\",\"On the neck\"],\"answer\":\"Between the shoulder blades\"}',21,3),(100,'{\"paragraph\":\"Abdominal thrusts also called the Heimlich maneuver are used when back blows fail. Stand behind the person, place one foot forward for stability, make a fist with one hand and place it just above the navel and below the breastbone, then cover it with your other hand. Pull sharply inward and upward in a J-shaped motion. Alternate five back blows with five abdominal thrusts until the object clears or the person becomes unconscious. If they become unconscious lower them carefully to the ground and begin CPR then call emergency services immediately.\",\"question\":\"What is the correct hand position for abdominal thrusts?\",\"options\":[\"On the chest above the heart\",\"On the back between shoulder blades\",\"On the lower stomach near the hips\",\"Just above the navel and below the breastbone\"],\"answer\":\"Just above the navel and below the breastbone\"}',21,4),(101,'{\"paragraph\":\"Drowning is the process of experiencing respiratory impairment from submersion or immersion in liquid. It can happen silently and very quickly ΓÇö a person can drown in as little as 20 to 60 seconds. Contrary to popular belief, drowning people rarely shout or wave for help. They are physiologically focused on keeping their mouth above water and cannot perform voluntary movements like waving. Recognising the quiet signs of drowning is the most critical skill a bystander can have.\",\"question\":\"How quickly can drowning cause death?\",\"options\":[\"In as little as 20 to 60 seconds\",\"Only after several minutes underwater\",\"Only if the person cannot swim\",\"After at least 5 minutes\"],\"answer\":\"In as little as 20 to 60 seconds\"}',22,0),(102,'{\"paragraph\":\"Signs of an active drowning person include: head low in the water with the mouth at water level, head tilted back with the mouth open, glassy or unfocused eyes, hair over the face, hyperventilating or gasping, trying to swim but making no progress, and a vertical body position in the water. They will not be able to call out for help or respond to your voice. If you see these signs act immediately ΓÇö every second without oxygen causes brain damage.\",\"question\":\"Which of these is a sign of active drowning?\",\"options\":[\"Waving both arms and shouting for help\",\"Head low in water with mouth at water level\",\"Floating calmly on the back\",\"Swimming quickly toward the edge\"],\"answer\":\"Head low in water with mouth at water level\"}',22,1),(103,'{\"paragraph\":\"The golden rule of water rescue is Reach, Throw, Row, Go in that order. First try to reach the person from safety using a towel, rope, branch, or pool noodle. If you cannot reach them throw a life ring or any floating object. If a boat is available row to them. Only enter the water yourself as a last resort and only if you are a trained rescuer ΓÇö a panicking drowning person can push even a strong swimmer underwater in their desperation to breathe.\",\"question\":\"What is the correct order of water rescue methods?\",\"options\":[\"Jump in first then throw a rope\",\"Call for help and wait only\",\"Reach, Throw, Row, Go\",\"Shout, Wave, Run, Dive\"],\"answer\":\"Reach, Throw, Row, Go\"}',22,2),(104,'{\"paragraph\":\"Once the person is safely out of the water check for responsiveness and normal breathing. If they are unresponsive and not breathing normally begin CPR immediately ΓÇö start with rescue breaths because drowning is a hypoxic arrest where the heart stops due to lack of oxygen rather than a cardiac problem. Give 2 rescue breaths then 30 chest compressions. Continue until the person breathes on their own or emergency services arrive. Do not stop to drain water from the lungs ΓÇö this wastes critical time.\",\"question\":\"Why do you start CPR for drowning with rescue breaths first?\",\"options\":[\"Rescue breaths are faster to perform\",\"Chest compressions cause vomiting when water is present\",\"Water must be removed from lungs first\",\"Drowning is a hypoxic arrest caused by lack of oxygen\"],\"answer\":\"Drowning is a hypoxic arrest caused by lack of oxygen\"}',22,3),(105,'{\"paragraph\":\"Even if a drowning person appears to recover fully at the scene, they must be taken to hospital immediately. Secondary drowning can occur hours later when water that entered the lungs causes inflammation and fluid buildup, leading to breathing difficulty or death up to 24 hours after the incident. Warning signs include persistent coughing, chest pain, extreme fatigue, and confusion after a water incident. Never dismiss these symptoms as minor ΓÇö always seek medical evaluation.\",\"question\":\"What is secondary drowning?\",\"options\":[\"A second drowning on the same day\",\"Drowning caused by a sudden cramp\",\"Delayed breathing difficulty caused by water in the lungs hours after the incident\",\"Drowning in shallow water only\"],\"answer\":\"Delayed breathing difficulty caused by water in the lungs hours after the incident\"}',22,4),(106,'{\"paragraph\":\"Floods are the most common and widespread natural disaster in India and worldwide. They occur when water overflows onto normally dry land due to heavy rainfall, overflowing rivers, dam failures, storm surges, or rapid snowmelt. Flash floods are the most dangerous type ΓÇö they develop within six hours of heavy rain, move at tremendous speed, and carry debris, vehicles, and even structures with them. Just 15 centimetres of fast-moving water can knock a person off their feet and 60 centimetres can carry away a car.\",\"question\":\"What is the most dangerous type of flood?\",\"options\":[\"Flash flood\",\"River overflow flood\",\"Coastal flood\",\"Dam release flood\"],\"answer\":\"Flash flood\"}',23,0),(107,'{\"paragraph\":\"Before a flood, preparation is essential. Keep an emergency kit with water, food, medicines, important documents in waterproof bags, a torch, and a battery-powered radio. Know your area flood risk and the nearest high ground. Move valuable items to upper floors. Never park vehicles in low-lying areas when rain is forecast. Sign up for official flood warnings from local authorities and never ignore evacuation orders ΓÇö your life is more valuable than any possession you leave behind.\",\"question\":\"Which item is most important in a flood emergency kit?\",\"options\":[\"Extra clothing\",\"Laptop and charger\",\"Clean water and food supply\",\"Spare furniture\"],\"answer\":\"Clean water and food supply\"}',23,1),(108,'{\"paragraph\":\"During a flood move immediately to higher ground and do not wait to see how bad it gets. Never walk through moving floodwater ΓÇö just 30 centimetres of moving water can sweep you off your feet. Stay off bridges over fast-moving water. If you are trapped in a building move to the highest floor but do not climb into a closed attic ΓÇö bring a torch and if necessary a tool to break through the roof to signal rescuers from above. Being visible from above is critical for helicopter rescue.\",\"question\":\"How much moving water can sweep a person off their feet?\",\"options\":[\"1 metre\",\"30 centimetres\",\"2 metres\",\"Only waist-deep water\"],\"answer\":\"30 centimetres\"}',23,2),(109,'{\"paragraph\":\"If you are trapped in a vehicle during a flood act quickly. A car can be swept away in 60 centimetres of water. Unlock your doors immediately. If water is rising inside the car open the window as soon as possible ΓÇö electric windows may stop working once submerged. If the window will not open use a hard object to break the corner of the window. Wait until pressure equalises before opening the door, then swim toward the surface following your bubbles upward if you become disoriented underwater.\",\"question\":\"What should you do first if trapped in a car during a flood?\",\"options\":[\"Call for help and wait inside\",\"Move to the back seat\",\"Turn on hazard lights first\",\"Unlock your doors immediately\"],\"answer\":\"Unlock your doors immediately\"}',23,3),(110,'{\"paragraph\":\"After a flood do not return home until authorities declare it safe. Floodwater is extremely hazardous ΓÇö it contains sewage, chemicals, debris, and live electrical current from downed power lines. Do not use tap water until officially tested. Wear rubber boots and gloves when cleaning up. Check your home for structural damage before entering. Photograph all damage for insurance claims before cleaning. Discard any food that has come into contact with floodwater including canned goods with compromised seals.\",\"question\":\"Why is floodwater hazardous after a flood recedes?\",\"options\":[\"It is too cold to touch safely\",\"It makes floors extremely slippery\",\"It contains sewage, chemicals, debris and live electrical current\",\"It causes skin rashes only\"],\"answer\":\"It contains sewage, chemicals, debris and live electrical current\"}',23,4),(111,'{\"paragraph\":\"An earthquake is a sudden violent shaking of the ground caused by movements in the Earth crust along fault lines. They strike without warning and last only seconds to minutes but can cause catastrophic damage. The magnitude scale measures energy released ΓÇö a magnitude 6 earthquake is 10 times stronger than a magnitude 5. India sits on one of the most seismically active zones in the world including the Himalayan belt, the northeast, and parts of Gujarat which experienced a devastating magnitude 7.7 earthquake in 2001.\",\"question\":\"What causes an earthquake?\",\"options\":[\"Heavy rainfall deep underground\",\"Movement in the Earth crust along fault lines\",\"Volcanic eruption at the surface only\",\"Underground water pressure building up\"],\"answer\":\"Movement in the Earth crust along fault lines\"}',24,0),(112,'{\"paragraph\":\"The most important action during an earthquake is Drop Cover and Hold On. Drop to your hands and knees immediately ΓÇö this prevents being knocked down and lets you move if needed. Take cover under a sturdy table or desk, or if no cover is available get against an interior wall away from windows. Hold on until the shaking stops. If no shelter is nearby cover your head and neck with your arms. Stay where you are ΓÇö do not run outside during shaking as most injuries occur from falling debris near building exits.\",\"question\":\"What is the correct action to take during an earthquake?\",\"options\":[\"Drop, Cover, and Hold On\",\"Run outside immediately to open space\",\"Stand in a doorway for protection\",\"Lie flat on the floor face down\"],\"answer\":\"Drop, Cover, and Hold On\"}',24,1),(113,'{\"paragraph\":\"Many earthquake myths can get you killed. Doorframes are not safe ΓÇö modern research shows they offer no more protection than other parts of the building and you are exposed to swinging doors and falling debris. The triangle of life theory ΓÇö hiding next to large objects ΓÇö is not endorsed by any major emergency management agency worldwide. The most dangerous places to be are near windows, exterior walls, and heavy furniture that can topple. Stay away from these even during aftershocks that follow the main event.\",\"question\":\"Why are doorframes NOT recommended as shelter during an earthquake?\",\"options\":[\"They are always the first structural element to collapse\",\"They are too narrow to stand in safely\",\"They attract falling glass from nearby windows\",\"They offer no extra protection and expose you to swinging doors and debris\"],\"answer\":\"They offer no extra protection and expose you to swinging doors and debris\"}',24,2),(114,'{\"paragraph\":\"If you are outdoors during an earthquake move away from buildings, streetlights, and utility wires immediately. Once in the open drop to the ground and stay there until the shaking stops. Most earthquake injuries outdoors are caused by falling debris from buildings and broken glass. Never re-enter a damaged building even after shaking stops. If you are near the coast move to high ground immediately after an earthquake ΓÇö tsunamis can follow within minutes and will not wait for an official warning to be issued.\",\"question\":\"What is the most important action after an earthquake if you are near the coast?\",\"options\":[\"Check your phone for news updates first\",\"Go back inside the nearest building\",\"Move to high ground immediately as a tsunami may follow\",\"Wait for an official warning before moving\"],\"answer\":\"Move to high ground immediately as a tsunami may follow\"}',24,3),(115,'{\"paragraph\":\"After an earthquake expect aftershocks ΓÇö smaller shakings that follow the main event sometimes for weeks. Check yourself and others for injuries before moving. If you smell gas leave the building immediately, leave the door open, and call the gas company from outside. Do not use lighters, candles, or electrical switches as a single spark can ignite a gas leak. Check for small fires and extinguish them immediately. Listen to emergency broadcasts and do not use the phone unless life is at risk ΓÇö keep lines free for rescue coordination.\",\"question\":\"What should you do if you smell gas after an earthquake?\",\"options\":[\"Open windows and stay inside to ventilate\",\"Leave immediately, leave the door open, and call from outside\",\"Light a candle to see the extent of the damage\",\"Turn on the main electrical switch to check the lights\"],\"answer\":\"Leave immediately, leave the door open, and call from outside\"}',24,4),(116,'{\"paragraph\":\"Lift or elevator accidents can include getting stuck between floors, power cuts during operation, door malfunctions, sudden free falls, and fire emergencies while inside. Modern elevators have multiple safety systems including emergency brakes, backup power, and alarm systems. However knowing what to do in each scenario can prevent panic-driven decisions that worsen the situation. The single most important rule in any elevator emergency is to stay calm and use the built-in safety systems rather than attempting self-rescue.\",\"question\":\"What is the most important rule in any elevator emergency?\",\"options\":[\"Pry open the doors and climb out immediately\",\"Jump to trigger the emergency safety brake\",\"Stay calm and use the built-in safety systems rather than attempting self-rescue\",\"Climb through the ceiling hatch to the top of the elevator\"],\"answer\":\"Stay calm and use the built-in safety systems rather than attempting self-rescue\"}',25,0),(117,'{\"paragraph\":\"If the lift stops and you are stuck, stay calm and do not panic. Press the emergency call button or alarm bell located on the control panel ΓÇö this alerts building management or a monitoring service. Use your mobile phone to call building security or emergency services. Never climb on top of the lift or attempt to force open the doors from inside ΓÇö the shaft contains moving counterweights and exposed electrical components that are extremely dangerous. The elevator cabin is the safest place to wait for trained rescuers.\",\"question\":\"What should you press first when stuck in an elevator?\",\"options\":[\"The emergency call button or alarm bell on the panel\",\"The door open button repeatedly until it works\",\"The highest floor button to reach the top\",\"The emergency stop button only\"],\"answer\":\"The emergency call button or alarm bell on the panel\"}',25,1),(118,'{\"paragraph\":\"In the event of a power cut while inside a lift the cabin will stop but will not fall ΓÇö modern elevators have electromagnetic brakes that automatically engage when power is lost. Emergency lighting should activate within seconds. If no emergency lighting activates use your phone torch. Stay calm, press the alarm, and wait. Do not force the doors. Power cuts in elevators are resolved quickly in most buildings and trained technicians will restore the lift or assist your exit safely within minutes.\",\"question\":\"What happens to a modern elevator brakes during a power cut?\",\"options\":[\"The cabin falls slowly to the ground floor\",\"The cabin rises automatically to the top floor\",\"The brakes have no effect during a power cut\",\"Electromagnetic brakes automatically engage and hold the cabin in place\"],\"answer\":\"Electromagnetic brakes automatically engage and hold the cabin in place\"}',25,2),(119,'{\"paragraph\":\"If a fire breaks out in the building while you are near a lift never use the elevator to escape ΓÇö lifts can malfunction in fire, trap you between floors, or open directly onto a fire floor. Always use the stairs. If you are already inside the lift when a fire alarm sounds press the button for the nearest floor, exit as soon as the doors open, and take the staircase. If you smell smoke inside the elevator press the alarm immediately and cover the gap below the doors with clothing to slow smoke entry.\",\"question\":\"Why should you never use an elevator during a building fire?\",\"options\":[\"Lifts are too slow during fire emergencies\",\"Lifts do not work when the fire alarm sounds\",\"Lifts can malfunction, trap you, or open directly onto a fire floor\",\"Lifts fill with water from the sprinkler system\"],\"answer\":\"Lifts can malfunction, trap you, or open directly onto a fire floor\"}',25,3),(120,'{\"paragraph\":\"A falling elevator is extremely rare due to multiple redundant safety systems but if it occurs press all floor buttons immediately to engage the motor on any available floor. Do not jump ΓÇö jumping just before impact is a myth and impossible to time correctly. Lie flat on the floor of the elevator spreading your weight evenly to distribute the impact force across the largest possible body surface area. Cover your head with your arms. The elevator cabin floor is specifically designed to absorb significant impact force.\",\"question\":\"What should you do if an elevator goes into free fall?\",\"options\":[\"Press the stop button only and hold the railing\",\"Jump just before it hits the bottom to reduce impact\",\"Stand in a corner with bent knees to absorb impact\",\"Lie flat on the floor, press all buttons, and cover your head\"],\"answer\":\"Lie flat on the floor, press all buttons, and cover your head\"}',25,4),(121,'{\"paragraph\":\"A tsunami is a series of enormous ocean waves triggered by an underwater earthquake, volcanic eruption, underwater landslide, or meteorite impact. The word tsunami means harbour wave in Japanese. Unlike normal wind waves, tsunami waves involve the entire column of ocean water from surface to seafloor and can travel at 800 km/h in deep ocean ΓÇö as fast as a jet aircraft. When they reach shallow coastal water they slow down but grow dramatically in height sometimes exceeding 30 metres, making them one of the deadliest natural disasters on Earth.\",\"question\":\"What is the speed of a tsunami wave in deep ocean?\",\"options\":[\"About 100 km/h similar to a fast car\",\"About 300 km/h similar to a bullet train\",\"Up to 800 km/h ΓÇö as fast as a jet aircraft\",\"The same speed as a normal ocean wave\"],\"answer\":\"Up to 800 km/h ΓÇö as fast as a jet aircraft\"}',26,0),(122,'{\"paragraph\":\"Nature gives three clear warning signs of an incoming tsunami. First a strong or prolonged earthquake near the coast lasting 20 seconds or more is itself a warning ΓÇö move to high ground immediately without waiting for any official alert. Second the ocean may recede dramatically exposing the seafloor ΓÇö this is called drawback and means a massive wave is about to arrive within minutes. Third a loud roaring sound like a freight train coming from the direction of the ocean. Any one of these three signs means you must act immediately.\",\"question\":\"What does it mean when the ocean suddenly recedes and exposes the seafloor?\",\"options\":[\"A tsunami wave is about to arrive ΓÇö move to high ground immediately\",\"The tide is simply going out unusually fast today\",\"An underwater earthquake happened far away with no local risk\",\"It is safe to walk on the exposed seafloor to collect fish\"],\"answer\":\"A tsunami wave is about to arrive ΓÇö move to high ground immediately\"}',26,1),(123,'{\"paragraph\":\"When a tsunami warning is issued or you observe natural warning signs move inland and uphill immediately. Go to at least 30 metres above sea level or 3 kilometres inland ΓÇö whichever you can reach faster. Do not wait to gather belongings. Do not go to the coast to watch ΓÇö thousands of people have died doing this. If you cannot reach high ground go to the upper floors of the tallest reinforced concrete building available as a last resort. Stay there until officials declare it safe as tsunamis come in multiple waves and the second or third wave is often the largest.\",\"question\":\"How high above sea level should you reach during a tsunami evacuation?\",\"options\":[\"5 metres above sea level is sufficient\",\"10 metres above sea level is the standard\",\"Any elevation above normal road level is acceptable\",\"At least 30 metres above sea level or 3 kilometres inland\"],\"answer\":\"At least 30 metres above sea level or 3 kilometres inland\"}',26,2),(124,'{\"paragraph\":\"If a tsunami wave catches you and you cannot escape look for something to hold onto or float on such as a door, piece of wood, or large container. Do not fight the current ΓÇö conserve your energy. Try to avoid debris which causes most tsunami injuries. After the wave recedes do not return to the coast ΓÇö the backwash current is also extremely dangerous and the next wave may arrive within minutes. Tsunami waves can continue arriving for up to eight hours after the first wave hits the coast.\",\"question\":\"How long can tsunami waves continue arriving after the first wave?\",\"options\":[\"Only for the first 30 minutes after the initial wave\",\"Up to eight hours after the first wave\",\"Only two waves ever occur in any tsunami\",\"Waves always stop arriving after exactly one hour\"],\"answer\":\"Up to eight hours after the first wave\"}',26,3),(125,'{\"paragraph\":\"The 2004 Indian Ocean tsunami killed over 230,000 people in 14 countries and remains one of the deadliest natural disasters in recorded history. India lost over 10,000 lives primarily in Tamil Nadu, Andaman and Nicobar Islands, Kerala, and Andhra Pradesh. Communities with tsunami education and established evacuation routes had significantly lower death rates. Today India has a Tsunami Early Warning System operated by INCOIS in Hyderabad that sends alerts within minutes of a triggering earthquake. Knowing your evacuation route and practising it regularly can save your life.\",\"question\":\"Which organisation operates India Tsunami Early Warning System?\",\"options\":[\"IMD ΓÇö India Meteorological Department\",\"NDRF ΓÇö National Disaster Response Force\",\"INCOIS ΓÇö Indian National Centre for Ocean Information Services\",\"ISRO ΓÇö Indian Space Research Organisation\"],\"answer\":\"INCOIS ΓÇö Indian National Centre for Ocean Information Services\"}',26,4),(126,'{\"paragraph\":\"Building structure collapse can be caused by earthquakes, explosions, fire damage to load-bearing elements, foundation failure, construction defects, overloading of floors, or age-related deterioration of materials. Collapses are sudden and leave little time to react. Understanding warning signs of a structurally compromised building can save your life before a collapse occurs. Warning signs include visible diagonal cracks at window corners, doors and windows that stick or no longer close properly, sagging floors or ceilings, and unusual sounds of creaking or popping from the structure.\",\"question\":\"Which of these is a warning sign of potential building collapse?\",\"options\":[\"Peeling paint on the exterior walls\",\"Diagonal cracks at window corners and doors that no longer close properly\",\"Discoloured water coming from taps\",\"A leaking roof during heavy rain\"],\"answer\":\"Diagonal cracks at window corners and doors that no longer close properly\"}',27,0),(127,'{\"paragraph\":\"If you are inside a building when collapse begins take cover immediately under a sturdy desk or table or against an interior load-bearing wall away from windows. Cover your head and neck with your arms. Do not run for exits during active collapse ΓÇö falling debris at stairwells and exits causes most collapse deaths. If trapped under debris do not light a match or lighter as gas leaks are common after collapse. Tap on pipes or walls to signal rescuers ΓÇö tapping carries further through rubble than shouting and preserves your energy and precious air supply.\",\"question\":\"How should you signal rescuers when trapped under collapse debris?\",\"options\":[\"Shout continuously as loudly as possible\",\"Light a match or lighter to attract visual attention\",\"Tap on pipes or walls ΓÇö tapping carries further and preserves your air\",\"Try to dig your way out alone toward any sound\"],\"answer\":\"Tap on pipes or walls ΓÇö tapping carries further and preserves your air\"}',27,1),(128,'{\"paragraph\":\"If trapped after a collapse preserve your air supply carefully. Cover your mouth and nose with a cloth to filter dust. Avoid unnecessary movement as it stirs up dust and consumes oxygen faster. Try to create a small space around you using your hands and any available tool by pushing debris away ΓÇö this is called void space creation and improves your survival odds significantly. If water is available conserve it carefully. The average survival window under rubble is 72 hours but has extended to over two weeks in documented cases where water was available.\",\"question\":\"What is the average survival window under collapse rubble?\",\"options\":[\"72 hours ΓÇö but can extend significantly with water available\",\"24 hours maximum under any circumstances\",\"Only 6 hours before oxygen runs out\",\"Exactly 1 week in all documented cases\"],\"answer\":\"72 hours ΓÇö but can extend significantly with water available\"}',27,2),(129,'{\"paragraph\":\"As a bystander at a collapse scene your most important action is calling emergency services immediately with the exact address and number of people believed trapped. Do not enter a partially collapsed structure ΓÇö secondary collapses kill more rescue volunteers than the original event. Wait for trained search and rescue teams who have specialised equipment to locate survivors. If someone is visible and accessible without entering the structure talk to them calmly to keep them conscious and guide them to stay still and conserve energy while professional help arrives.\",\"question\":\"Why should bystanders NOT enter a partially collapsed building?\",\"options\":[\"Rescue teams will refuse to come if bystanders have entered\",\"The air inside is immediately toxic after collapse\",\"It is illegal to enter collapsed buildings under any circumstances\",\"Secondary collapses are common and kill more rescue volunteers than the original event\"],\"answer\":\"Secondary collapses are common and kill more rescue volunteers than the original event\"}',27,3),(130,'{\"paragraph\":\"After a building collapse event authorities will establish a search and rescue perimeter. Trained Urban Search and Rescue teams use acoustic listening devices, search cameras threaded through small gaps, and trained search dogs to locate survivors. Survivors should make noise at regular intervals ΓÇö three taps or three shouts is the international signal for a person in distress. If you have a phone with any battery remaining even without a SIM card call 112 which works without a SIM card and will ping the nearest tower to relay your location to emergency services.\",\"question\":\"What is the international distress signal for a person trapped under rubble?\",\"options\":[\"One long continuous shout repeated every minute\",\"Five rapid taps followed by complete silence\",\"Three taps or three shouts repeated at regular intervals\",\"Waving a light source rapidly in any direction\"],\"answer\":\"Three taps or three shouts repeated at regular intervals\"}',27,4),(131,'{\"paragraph\":\"A stampede occurs when a large crowd of people suddenly moves in the same direction in panic, creating a crushing force that can kill people even without any physical contact with the initial panic source. The crushing pressure in a dense crowd can exceed 4500 newtons ΓÇö enough to bend steel barriers. People do not die from being trampled in most stampede deaths ΓÇö they die from compressive asphyxia where the crowd pressure prevents the chest from expanding to breathe. India experiences several deadly stampedes each year often at religious gatherings, concerts, and political rallies.\",\"question\":\"What is the main cause of death in a stampede?\",\"options\":[\"Being trampled directly underfoot by the crowd\",\"Heart attack from extreme fear and panic\",\"Compressive asphyxia ΓÇö crowd chest pressure preventing breathing\",\"Dehydration from the intense heat of a large crowd\"],\"answer\":\"Compressive asphyxia ΓÇö crowd chest pressure preventing breathing\"}',28,0),(132,'{\"paragraph\":\"Crowd crush begins to become dangerous when density exceeds four to five people per square metre. At this density people lose the ability to move independently and are carried entirely by crowd flow. Warning signs of an impending stampede or crush include a sudden surge where everyone moves at once, a ripple effect you can see moving through the crowd from a distance, people around you losing their footing, screaming from a direction you cannot see the cause of, and the sound of crowd noise shifting from a roar to high-pitched screaming.\",\"question\":\"At what crowd density does movement become uncontrollable and dangerous?\",\"options\":[\"Ten or more people per square metre\",\"Four to five people per square metre\",\"Only when people are physically touching shoulder to shoulder\",\"Only in outdoor events without proper barriers\"],\"answer\":\"Four to five people per square metre\"}',28,1),(133,'{\"paragraph\":\"If you find yourself in a dangerously dense crowd the most important technique is to position your body to protect your chest and airway. Keep your arms up in front of your chest in a boxer stance ΓÇö this creates a small protected space around your chest allowing you to breathe even when surrounded by pressing bodies. Move diagonally toward the edge of the crowd rather than against the main flow. Never bend down to pick up dropped items ΓÇö you will not be able to stand again in a dense crowd. Do not fight the crowd flow directly as this exhausts you and creates dangerous turbulence.\",\"question\":\"Why should you keep your arms up in front of your chest in a crowd crush?\",\"options\":[\"It helps you physically push other people away from you\",\"It signals rescuers and security that you urgently need help\",\"It keeps your hands free to grab onto fixed barriers\",\"It creates a protected space that allows you to continue breathing\"],\"answer\":\"It creates a protected space that allows you to continue breathing\"}',28,2),(134,'{\"paragraph\":\"If you fall in a stampede the survival position is critical. Curl into a ball on your side drawing your knees up to your chest, cover your head with your arms, and face in the direction of crowd movement. This position protects your vital organs and head from impact. Try to get up as quickly as possible by timing a rise with a momentary gap in the crowd ΓÇö push up on all fours first then stand. Screaming for help loudly draws attention from bystanders on the edge of the crowd who may be able to pull you out to safety.\",\"question\":\"What is the correct survival position if you fall in a stampede?\",\"options\":[\"Curl on your side with knees to chest, cover head, face direction of crowd movement\",\"Lie completely flat on your back with both arms stretched wide out\",\"Stand up immediately no matter what at any cost\",\"Roll quickly in any direction to avoid being stepped on\"],\"answer\":\"Curl on your side with knees to chest, cover head, face direction of crowd movement\"}',28,3),(135,'{\"paragraph\":\"Event organisers and attendees both have critical roles in stampede prevention. Organisers must ensure clearly marked multiple exit points, crowd flow management with barriers, trained crowd monitors, and emergency communication systems. As an attendee always identify the nearest two exits when you enter any crowded venue ΓÇö not just the main entrance you came through. Stay near the edges of crowds rather than the densely packed centre. If you sense a crowd becoming dangerously dense leave early before pressure builds ΓÇö being cautious costs nothing but staying in a building crush can cost your life.\",\"question\":\"What should every attendee do first upon entering any crowded venue?\",\"options\":[\"Find the centre of the crowd for the best view of the event\",\"Register your presence with event security personnel\",\"Identify the nearest two exits ΓÇö not just the main entrance\",\"Find the food and water stations for later reference\"],\"answer\":\"Identify the nearest two exits ΓÇö not just the main entrance\"}',28,4),(136,'{\"paragraph\":\"A cyclone is a massive rotating storm system with sustained winds exceeding 119 km/h forming over warm tropical ocean waters. The same storm is called a hurricane in the Atlantic and a typhoon in the Pacific ΓÇö but they are all the same phenomenon. Cyclones are categorised from Category 1 minimal to Category 5 catastrophic based on wind speed. They bring destructive winds, torrential rainfall, and storm surges which are walls of ocean water pushed ashore that cause more deaths than wind alone. India eastern coastline facing the Bay of Bengal is one of the most cyclone-prone regions in the entire world.\",\"question\":\"What causes more deaths in a cyclone than wind alone?\",\"options\":[\"Heavy rainfall from the storm bands\",\"Lightning strikes during the storm\",\"Extreme heat generated by the storm eye\",\"Storm surge ΓÇö walls of ocean water pushed ashore\"],\"answer\":\"Storm surge ΓÇö walls of ocean water pushed ashore\"}',29,0),(137,'{\"paragraph\":\"When a cyclone warning is issued for your area preparation time is very limited. Board up windows with plywood or install storm shutters. Fill bathtubs and large containers with clean water as supply will be disrupted. Charge all devices and prepare a go-bag with documents, medicines, food, and water for at least 72 hours. Move to an evacuation shelter if ordered ΓÇö never ignore official evacuation orders from the India Meteorological Department. The risk of staying in a low-lying coastal area during a severe cyclone is fatal.\",\"question\":\"How many hours of supplies should a cyclone go-bag contain?\",\"options\":[\"At least 12 hours of supplies\",\"At least 24 hours of supplies\",\"At least 72 hours of supplies\",\"At least 1 week of supplies\"],\"answer\":\"At least 72 hours of supplies\"}',29,1),(138,'{\"paragraph\":\"During a cyclone stay indoors away from windows and glass doors. The safest areas inside a building are an interior room on the lowest floor, a bathroom without windows, or a corridor. If the eye of the cyclone passes over you the wind will calm completely and the sky may clear ΓÇö do not go outside. This calm lasts only minutes before the back eyewall hits with equal or greater force from the opposite direction. Many cyclone deaths in India occur when people venture outside during the eye thinking the storm has completely passed.\",\"question\":\"What should you do when the eye of the cyclone passes and it becomes suddenly calm?\",\"options\":[\"Go outside quickly to assess damage before the next band arrives\",\"Move to a different building while conditions are calm\",\"Stay inside ΓÇö the back eyewall will hit with equal force from the opposite direction\",\"Turn off the generator outside while it is calm and safe\"],\"answer\":\"Stay inside ΓÇö the back eyewall will hit with equal force from the opposite direction\"}',29,2),(139,'{\"paragraph\":\"If you are caught in a cyclone outdoors and cannot reach shelter find the sturdiest nearby structure such as a concrete building and stay on the lowest floor away from windows. If no structure is available lie flat in a ditch or low-lying area and cover your head ΓÇö wind speed is significantly lower close to the ground. Never shelter under a tree ΓÇö trees are the first casualties of high cyclone winds. Avoid bridges, overpasses, and any elevated structures which experience the strongest wind forces during a cyclone.\",\"question\":\"Where should you lie if caught in a cyclone outdoors with no shelter available?\",\"options\":[\"Flat in a ditch or low-lying area covering your head\",\"Under the largest nearby tree for overhead cover\",\"On a bridge away from the water below\",\"On the roof of the nearest building for visibility\"],\"answer\":\"Flat in a ditch or low-lying area covering your head\"}',29,3),(140,'{\"paragraph\":\"After a cyclone do not return to evacuated areas until authorities declare them safe. Avoid downed power lines ΓÇö assume every line is live and deadly. Do not drive through flooded roads left by the storm surge. Beware of weakened structures that look intact from outside but may collapse without warning. Document all damage with photographs before cleaning up. Contaminated water sources are a major post-cyclone health risk in coastal India ΓÇö boil all water or use bottled water until official clearance. Report gas leaks, injuries, and trapped persons to emergency services immediately.\",\"question\":\"What should you assume about every downed power line after a cyclone?\",\"options\":[\"It is safe if it is not visibly sparking\",\"It is safe if it fell into standing water\",\"It is safe to approach after waiting 30 minutes\",\"It is live and deadly ΓÇö stay far away and report it immediately\"],\"answer\":\"It is live and deadly ΓÇö stay far away and report it immediately\"}',29,4);
